.TH BSDR_MICRELAY 1 "2026-07-04" "bsdrX" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
bsdr_micrelay \- router-side owner-mic relay for bsdrX
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bsdr_micrelay
.BI \-\-iface " IF"
.BI \-\-quest " HEADSET-IP"
.BI \-\-to " HOST:PORT"
.SH DESCRIPTION
A Bigscreen VR headset sends its microphone only to the Bigscreen cloud (as plain Opus RTP); there
is no LAN mic-upload channel. On a wired LAN,
.BR bsdr_agent (1)
can ARP-spoof to intercept that stream, but over Wi-Fi it cannot \(em the access point bridges
per-station traffic, so the headset's mic never reaches the host's radio.
.PP
The router, however, is in the path for every packet the headset sends.
.B bsdr_micrelay
runs on the router, captures the headset's outbound UDP with libpcap, and forwards the raw IPv4
packets to a bsdrX host running
.BR "bsdr_agent \-\-sniff\-remote" .
bsdrX then decodes them through its normal owner-mic path, exposing the
.B BSDR-Quest-OwnerMic
virtual microphone and feeding voice computer-control. Because it captures the headset's own
uplink, the result is the owner's voice only \(em no room mixing, no MITM, no monitor mode.
.PP
.B Cloud voice substitution.
When bsdrX has the voice changer's \(lqsubstitute into the cloud\(rq option on, it re\-encodes the
changed voice and sends the modified RTP back to the relay over the same UDP link. The relay then
installs an
.B iptables
FORWARD DROP for the headset\(->cloud flow (suppressing the originals) and forwards bsdrX's modified
audio to the cloud from its own socket, so the room hears the changed voice. This needs root on the
router (for the DROP rule); the relay does no codec work itself, and reverts to passthrough
automatically if bsdrX stops driving it. It is controlled entirely by bsdrX \(em no extra flags.
.PP
The binary is fully static (bundled libpcap), so it can be copied straight onto a router. Prebuilt
binaries for common router and PC architectures ship in
.B bsdrX_relay.zip
(see
.BR distribute.sh );
an OpenWRT package recipe is in
.BR openwrt/bsdr-micrelay/ .
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-\-iface " IF"
Capture interface \(em the router LAN/bridge the headset is on (for example
.BR br-lan ).
.TP
.BI \-\-quest " HEADSET-IP"
The headset's IPv4 address. Only packets from this source are forwarded.
.TP
.BI \-\-to " HOST:PORT"
The bsdrX host and the UDP port it listens on
.RB ( "bsdr_agent \-\-sniff\-remote PORT" ).
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show usage and exit.
.SH REQUIREMENTS
Raw packet capture needs root or the
.B CAP_NET_RAW
capability on the router. libpcap is statically linked into the prebuilt binaries; when building
from source it is the only dependency.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
On the router (headset at 192.168.1.50, bsdrX host at 192.168.1.10, port 45099):
.B bsdr_micrelay \-\-iface br\-lan \-\-quest 192.168.1.50 \-\-to 192.168.1.10:45099
.TP
On the bsdrX host:
.B bsdr_agent \-\-sniff\-remote 45099
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR bsdr_agent (1).
